'''Okami Shrine''' (意賀美神社) is a [[:en:Shinto shrine|Shinto shrine]] located in [[Hirakata City|枚方市]], [[Osaka Prefecture|大阪府]], Japan. It is a {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|2=ja|3=式内社|qq=draft|1=Shikinaisha|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikinaisha|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikinaisha|qq=}} and was classified as a {{ill|Murasha|ja|村社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Murasha|qq=}} under the [[:en:Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines]]. The shrine is near [[Hirakata-shi Station|枚方市駅]].
== Deities == The shrine enshrines Takeminakata-no-Kami (高龗神) as its main deity, along with {{ill|Susanoo|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto|ja|素盞嗚尊|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Susanoo|13=User:Immanuelle/Susanoo-no-Mikoto|qq=}}, [[:en:Oyamakui no Kami|Ōyamatsumi]], and {{ill|Ōkuninushi|ja|大国主神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōkuninushi|qq=}} as auxiliary deities. Susanoo was originally worshipped at Suga Shrine, while Ōyamatsumi and Ōkuninushi were enshrined at Hiyoshi Shrine. These were merged into Okami Shrine during the [[:en:Meiji era|Meiji era]]<ref name="OkamiShrine">{{Cite web|url=http://osakadai3shibu.kilo.jp/jinja/hirakata/jinja/okami.html |title=Okami Shrine |publisher=Osaka Prefecture Shrine Association |accessdate=2020-07-18 }}</ref>.
== History == [[File:河内名所図会 枚方萬年寺.png|thumb|Illustration of Mannenji from {{ill|Kawachi Meisho Zue|ja|河内名所図会|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kawachi Meisho Zue|qq=}}]] Originally located approximately 100 meters south of its current site in the former Ikaga Village, the shrine's exact foundation date is unknown. It is said to have been established on the estate of {{ill|Ika-shikoo|ja|伊香色男|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ika-shikoo|qq=}}, an ancestor of the [[:en:Mononobe clan|Mononobe clan]] and a descendant of {{ill|Nigi-hayahi-no-Mikoto|ja|饒速日命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nigi-hayahi-no-Mikoto|qq=}}. Takeminakata-no-Kami, a water deity, was worshipped as the guardian of the [[:en:Yodo River|Yodo River]] and is listed as a minor shrine in the [[:en:Engishiki|Engishiki]]. It became the tutelary shrine of Ikaga Village and was designated a village shrine in 1872 (Meiji 5).
The current location was previously occupied by Suga Shrine, originally called Gozu Tenno Shrine (Gion Shrine), established in 872 CE during the [[:en:Zhenguan|Jōgan era]]. The shrine was founded to pray for the end of a plague by {{ill|Shōbō|ja|聖宝|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōbō|qq=}}, the founder of {{ill|Mannenji Temple|ja|長松山万年寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mannenji Temple|qq=}}, which was abolished during the [[:en:Haibutsu kishaku|Haibutsu kishaku]] movement in 1870. Suga Shrine also became a village shrine in 1872.
Hiyoshi Shrine, previously known as Sannō Daigongen, was the guardian deity of the nearby Okamura area. Its origins are unclear but may trace back to either a drifted [[:en:Hiyoshi Taisha|Hiyoshi Taisha]] divine body or a shrine established by [[:en:Saichō|Saichō]]. After being destroyed during the [[:en:Ōnin War|Ōnin War]], it was rebuilt in 1600 by Matsudaira Naizen-no-kami Masayasu, lord of Hirakata Castle.
In 1909 (Meiji 42), Suga Shrine and Hiyoshi Shrine were merged into Okami Shrine. Due to space limitations, the shrine was relocated the following day to its current site on Mannenji Hill, the former location of Suga Shrine<ref name="OkamiShrine"/>.
== Grounds == The shrine grounds include the following: * {{ill|Inari Shrine|ja|稲荷社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Inari Shrine|qq=}}: Built in [[:en:Nagare-zukuri|Nagare-zukuri]], late 18th century<ref name="HirakataShrines">{{Cite book|title=Hirakata City Report III: Shrine Architecture in Hirakata|publisher=Hirakata City Board of Education|date=1994|pages=67-71}}</ref>. * Kotohira Shrine: Built in [[:en:Nagare-zukuri|Nagare-zukuri]], around 1720 (Kyōhō 5). Believed to have been the former main hall of Suga Shrine, though this is uncertain<ref name="HirakataShrines"/>. * Stone Pagoda: A nine-tiered pagoda dating back to the [[:en:Northern and Southern Courts period (disambiguation)|Nanboku-chō period]] to early [[:en:Muromachi period|Muromachi period]]. Originally thought to be a thirteen-tiered structure<ref name="HirakataShrines"/>.
[[File:Hirakata hakkei Mannenjiyama no ryokuin 20070101.jpg|thumb|Mannenji Hill, one of the {{ill|Eight Views of Hirakata|ja|枚方八景|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Eight Views of Hirakata|qq=}}]] The site is renowned for its approximately 100 plum trees, making it a popular plum-viewing spot<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.okeihan.net/recommend/ume/detail/05_okami.php |title=Plum Viewing at Okami Shrine |publisher=Keihan Railway |accessdate=2020-07-17 }}</ref>.
== Cultural Properties == * [[:en:Sangaku|Sangaku]]: Dedicated in 1861 (Bunkyū 1) by Iwata Seiyō<ref name="OkamiShrine"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.city.hirakata.osaka.jp/0000002755.html#link-si |title=Hirakata City Cultural Properties |publisher=Hirakata City |accessdate=2020-07-18 }}</ref>. == See Also == * {{ill|Mannenyama Kofun|ja|万年山古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mannenyama Kofun|qq=}}
